---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-spain', text: 'Leaving Spanish Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'convenio-especial', text: 'Convenio Especial Option', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-spain', text: 'Returning to Spain', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Sanitas Review', href: '/providers/sanitas' },
  { title: 'Spain Non-Lucrative Visa', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-spain-non-lucrative-visa' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Latin America Insurance', href: '/best/latin-america-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'spanishSupport', header: 'Spanish Support' },
  { key: 'latamNetwork', header: 'Latin America' },
  { key: 'spainCoverage', header: 'Spain Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', spanishSupport: 'Full', latamNetwork: 'Strong', spainCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Sanitas Global', spanishSupport: 'Full (Spanish)', latamNetwork: 'Good', spainCoverage: 'Included', price: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'ASISA Internacional', spanishSupport: 'Full (Spanish)', latamNetwork: 'Limited', spainCoverage: 'Included', price: '€130/mo' },
  { provider: 'Mapfre Global', spanishSupport: 'Full (Spanish)', latamNetwork: 'Excellent', spainCoverage: 'Included', price: '€170/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', spanishSupport: 'Yes', latamNetwork: 'Good', spainCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€200/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Spanish Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Spanish expats. From Sanitas Global to international options, find coverage that works in Latin America, Europe, and beyond."
  headline="Best Insurance for Spanish Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Whether you're heading to Latin America, other EU countries, or further afield, here's how to stay covered while maintaining your connection to Spain."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/spanish-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Spanish expats have strong ties to Latin America, making Spanish-language support essential. Here's what we recommend based on destination and needs:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Spanish expats. Full Spanish support, strong networks worldwide, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Sanitas Global:</strong> Spanish company (Bupa-owned) with excellent Spanish-language service. Great for maintaining familiar healthcare relationships.</li>
    <li><strong>Mapfre Global:</strong> Spanish insurer with outstanding Latin American networks. Ideal for expats in Mexico, Argentina, or other LATAM countries.</li>
    <li><strong>ASISA Internacional:</strong> Budget-friendly Spanish option with good EU coverage. Lower premiums for younger expats.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium international option for those wanting top-tier coverage outside Spanish networks.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Going to Latin America?"
    description="Spanish expats often move to Latin America where language and cultural ties are strong. Mapfre and Cigna have the strongest LATAM networks. Sanitas is good but more EU-focused."
    buttonText="Compare LATAM Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-spain">Leaving Spanish Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Spain's public healthcare system (Sistema Nacional de Salud) provides excellent coverage for residents. When you leave, several things change:
  </p>

  <h3>Tarjeta Sanitaria and Empadronamiento</h3>
  <p>
    Your Spanish health card (tarjeta sanitaria) is linked to your empadronamiento (census registration). When you deregister from your municipality, you lose access to public healthcare. Your EHIC remains valid for EU travel emergencies until it expires.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Insurance in Spain</h3>
  <p>
    If you have private Spanish insurance (Sanitas, Adeslas, Mapfre, ASISA), these typically don't cover you long-term abroad. Options:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Cancel and get international coverage</li>
    <li>Switch to the same company's international product if available</li>
    <li>Maintain Spanish coverage for visits home and get separate international insurance</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Autónomos and Social Security</h3>
  <p>
    Self-employed workers (autónomos) who leave Spain can maintain voluntary Social Security contributions through a convenio especial. This affects pension rights more than healthcare, but it's worth understanding.
  </p>

  <h2 id="convenio-especial">Convenio Especial Option</h2>
  <p>
    The convenio especial allows Spanish citizens abroad to maintain certain Social Security rights. Here's what it covers:
  </p>

  <h3>What Convenio Especial Provides</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Continued accumulation of pension contributions</li>
    <li>Access to Spanish public healthcare during visits (with limitations)</li>
    <li>Maintaining your connection to the Spanish system</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Limitations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Does NOT provide healthcare abroad—you still need international insurance</li>
    <li>Coverage in Spain is limited to urgent/necessary care during visits</li>
    <li>Monthly cost varies based on your contribution base</li>
    <li>Must apply within 12 months of leaving Spain</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Consular Registration</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Register with your local Spanish consulate when you move abroad. This is required for voting, passport renewal, and can help with accessing certain rights including emergency healthcare coordination through consular services.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage with full Spanish-language support. Their Global Health Plan comes in three tiers (Silver, Gold, Platinum) with coverage from €1 million to unlimited. Strong networks across Latin America make this ideal for Spanish expats in the Americas.
  </p>

  <p>
    Claims processing is efficient, with Spanish-speaking representatives available 24/7. Direct billing works at major hospitals throughout Latin America, Europe, and Asia.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Spanish expats who want comprehensive global coverage with native Spanish support.
  </p>

  <h3>Sanitas Global</h3>
  <p>
    Sanitas is Spain's largest private health insurer, owned by Bupa. Sanitas Global extends their coverage internationally while maintaining the Spanish service experience. If you're already a Sanitas customer in Spain, the transition is seamless.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans include Spain coverage automatically, so visits home are straightforward. EU networks are strong, though LATAM coverage is less comprehensive than Mapfre or Cigna.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Spanish expats in Europe who want to stay with a familiar Spanish provider.
  </p>

  <h3>Mapfre Global</h3>
  <p>
    Mapfre is a major Spanish insurer with excellent presence throughout Latin America. Their international health plans are specifically designed for Spanish-speaking expats, with outstanding networks in Mexico, Argentina, Chile, Colombia, and throughout Central America.
  </p>

  <p>
    All service is in Spanish, claims are straightforward, and the Mapfre brand is recognized throughout the Spanish-speaking world. Spain coverage is included in all plans.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Spanish expats in Latin America who want strong local networks and familiar Spanish service.
  </p>

  <h3>ASISA Internacional</h3>
  <p>
    ASISA offers budget-friendly international coverage for Spanish expats. While networks are more limited than Cigna or Mapfre, pricing is competitive and service is fully in Spanish. Good option for younger expats or those in EU countries where ASISA has partnerships.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Budget-conscious Spanish expats, particularly those staying within the EU.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Spanish-Language Quotes"
    description="Compare prices from Spanish and international insurers. Most offer quotes and service entirely in Spanish."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-spain">Returning to Spain</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Spanish healthcare is relatively straightforward for Spanish citizens:
  </p>

  <h3>Re-registering (Empadronamiento)</h3>
  <p>
    Register at your local ayuntamiento when you return. This is the first step to accessing public healthcare. You'll need proof of address (rental contract, property deed, or family member's authorization).
  </p>

  <h3>Tarjeta Sanitaria</h3>
  <p>
    Apply for your health card at your local centro de salud or through the regional health service. Processing typically takes 1-2 weeks. In the meantime, your empadronamiento certificate serves as proof of healthcare entitlement.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Insurance Transition</h3>
  <p>
    If returning to private Spanish insurance, you may face waiting periods for pre-existing conditions. Some insurers waive these if you had continuous coverage abroad—keep documentation of your international insurance.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does my EHIC work abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Your Spanish EHIC covers emergency care in other EU/EEA countries. It's not valid outside Europe and doesn't cover routine care or repatriation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep Sanitas abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Standard Sanitas plans are for Spain residents. For long-term abroad, you need Sanitas Global or another international policy.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is convenio especial worth it?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">For pension contributions, possibly yes. For healthcare, it's limited. You still need international insurance for actual coverage abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Which insurer is best for Mexico?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Mapfre has the strongest Mexican network among Spanish insurers. Cigna is also excellent. Both offer full Spanish-language service.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use Spanish doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In cities with Spanish communities (Miami, Buenos Aires, London), you can often find Spanish-speaking doctors. All international insurers cover any licensed physician.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my Spanish pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Consider convenio especial to continue accumulating pension rights. Spain has bilateral agreements with many countries that help coordinate benefits.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Spanish expats have excellent options, especially those heading to Latin America where Spanish insurers have strong networks. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive coverage with native Spanish support. <strong>Mapfre Global</strong> is ideal for Latin America with outstanding regional networks.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Sanitas Global</strong> makes sense for those already with Sanitas who want continuity, while <strong>ASISA Internacional</strong> offers budget-friendly coverage for younger expats or EU destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, consider convenio especial for pension rights, and register with your local consulate. Keep documentation of continuous insurance coverage—it helps when returning to Spanish private insurance.
  </p>

</PageShell>
